entry.title: [iOS] Fix compromised/muted password details not updating correctly
entry.content:
When updates on saved passwords' issues occurred while the Password

Manager was opened, the updates were not reflected in the passwords'

details. In other words, if a password check detected a new compromised

password, the compromised warning was not present in the details of that

password immediately. The warning would only be present after quitting

the Password Manager and re-opening it. This was due to an early return

in PasswordManagerViewController that was preventing the UI from being

updated when it should have been. This CL fixes the condition of the

early return so that the UI is updated when needed.



Fixed: 1434072

results in corrupted traces. This CL fixes this and adds a regression

test.

entry.title: [omnibox][post-ac][ml] Cancel pending requests in `StopHelper()`.
entry.content:
Currently:

- `StopHelper()` does not cancel debounce requests.

- `StopHelper()` cancels ULR scoring requests ONLY if the popup is

closed.



This CL:

async pass kicks off a URL scoring request.

user pressed the down/up/left/right arrow, the user pessed

entry.title: Revert "[uia] MoveEndpointByRange not working in certain scenarios."
entry.content:
This reverts commit 1c90ae736c562efd7af01f46dce817f0d24a5e6a.



Reason for revert: https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1435023



Original change's description:

> [uia] MoveEndpointByRange not working in certain scenarios.

>

> This CL introduces a fix where MoveEndpointByRange UIA API

> was previously returning the incorrect values in circumstances where

> for example, we had a `
` with a child `

`.

>

> Before the fix, the API would call functions that operate under the

> assumption that IA2 APIs are calling them, so they would behave a

> certain way as `embedded object characters` would be added to elements

> as per IA2 specifications. UIA API's have different expectations

> regarding computing the text on a node that has no text itself.

> IA2 expects the content to be exposed as a single embedded object

> character, whereas UIA expects to get the text from the

> text content of the subtree of that node.

> So we have to make sure that when these functions are called, the `AXEmbeddedObjectBehavior::kSuppressCharacter`

> global variable is set, which tells the functions whether or not to

> operate under the IA2 expectations regarding the embedded object

> character.

>

> The incorrect behavior and tree structure on the added test could

> be seen in web apps such as Google Docs and Word for the web when making

> comments.

>

entry.title: [omnibox] Delete a DCHECK that is not always true
entry.content:
After looking at this code, the DCHECK may sometimes be legitimately

hit, and it's not a programmer error.



The DCHECK used the current system time as a threshold.



But the history iterator issued the query using the the current system

time from when it began the query.



Since the query takes a finite amount of time, the current system time

has changed. Therefore the DCHECK may sometimes fail.



I expect that's why there's crash reports for this DCHECK.



I'm just deleting this DCHECK because it's not an invariant. I also

don't think it's worth re-writing the DCHECK to pass using a stored

time threshold.

entry.title: Fix WebGPU resource destruction race condition
entry.content:
Problem: When tearing down a web page that uses WebGPU in a worker, the

order of garbage collection between the placeholder canvas and the

worker thread is non-deterministic. This means that it may not be

possible to return the CanvasResource held by the placeholder canvas

back to the thread where it was created. The problem with this is that

the ExternalCanvasResource objects used by WebGPU may hold a

viz::ReleaseCallback object, which is not thread safe. Even though the

callback is never called on the wrong thread, simply destroying it on

the wrong thread causes problems because objects bound to the callback

closure may end up being unref'ed and destroyed on the wrong thread.



The solution implemented in this CL avoids transiting the

viz::ReleaseCallback through other threads, which guarantees it will

never be destroyed on the wrong thread. We basically detach the

release callback from the CanvasResource before dispatching it to the

placeholder canvas (on the main thread), and we re-attach the callback

when the resource is returned to its thread of origin (for final

destruction or recycling).

entry.title: Configure randomized response rates in terms of epsilon
entry.content:
This CL modifies the AttributionConfig to use the randomized response

epsilon level as a parameter instead of specific event/navigation

randomized response rates. Interop tests configs are updated accordingly.



This epsilon parameter is used to dynamically compute the RR rates at

runtime, as a function of the number of possible output states in each

source type variant.



For now this is hard-coded, but in a follow-up the number of output

states will be made dynamic based on the event_report_window parameter.



This CL has a few observable behavior changes. Now that we compute RR

rates dynamically we no longer apply ad-hoc rounding when computing the

`randomized_trigger_rate` for a source. This means that:

1. We actually apply a very slightly higher RR rate for nav sources

and slightly lower RR rate for event sources.

navigation sources: .0024 --> 0.002426322167...

event sources: .0.0000025 --> 0.000002494582...



2. The `randomized_trigger_rate` field in event-level reports is

uniformly rounded to 7 decimal places across both event and

navigation sources.



Bug: 1434755

entry.title: input_injector_wayland: Fix libei session tear down
entry.content:
We want to stop injecting inputs when we don't have

the screencast stream/virtual monitor. We already

do this by registering Core class's shutdown callbakc

that gets triggered by the desktop capturer cleanup.

We were also calling this cleanup again when the

injector is getting destroyed - this is redundant

and is removed in the patch.



Other changes:

- Ensures that the cleanup (now renamed

as shutdown) in the remote desktop portal injector

module happens on the same thread to which the object

was bound initially. Before this change the could

have been done on any thread where this object was

destroyed.



- Fixes the cleanup order in the

event watcher module where we close the file

descriptor before destroying the source. This is

followed by unref-ing the `ei` handle. This setup

now is similar to how mutter does its main loop

event cleanup for `libeis`.



- Improves the state machine of the injector by

making the states more explicit and ensuring the

transitions happen in a sequence.



- Removes an unused method (i.e. `InjectScrollWheelClicks`)

entry.title: [CodeHealth] Fix UnsafeDanglingUntriaged in BackgroundContentsService
entry.content:
This CL is part of a larger cleanup effort to triage dangling pointers

and ensure they aren't the cause of memory issues in Chrome. See:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/164SnySRX6MZgFkX8qLLLClTnZ0S8s5wLiNFWNyQ8f4E/edit



`ShowBalloon` binds a raw pointer to Profile when creating a callback

passed to `NotificationImageReady`. But this Profile can be destroyed

before the callback gets called.



This CL handles this situation by:

1) Adding a dependency on NotificationDisplayService in

BackgroundContentsServiceFactory to ensure the

NotificationDisplayService doesn't get destroyed

before the BackgroundContentsService.

2) Converting ShowBalloon and NotificationImageReady from

free functions to private members of BackgroundContentsService

3) Binding a WeakPtr to BackgroundContentsService in the callback

created in ShowBallon.



This CL also removes the CommandLine* argument passed to the

constructor of BackgroundContentsService, since this is unused.

entry.title: [android/perf] Avoid useless & expensive OS notification calls by Sync
entry.content:
Calls to add and cancel notifications are expensive, see linked bug.

Before this CL, SyncErrorNotifier did NotificationManagerProxy.cancel()

even if there weren't any notifications. It also attempted to notify()

the same notification multiple times.

Now the notification state is cached in a field and used to decide

whether to issue the expensive calls.

entry.title: [balance-text] Fix break token propagation
entry.content:
When crrev.com/c/4369820 tried to move `PropagatedBreakTokens`

out of `NGLineBreaker`, it did:

1. Move propagated break tokens while line breaking to

`NGLineInfo`.

2. Move propagated break tokens while `CreateLine` to

`NGInlineChildLayoutContext`.



2 was not correct, because the algorithm may retry not only

line breaking but also `CreateLine` in certain cases, and

propagated break tokens from non-final `CreateLine` should not

be added to `NGInlineChildLayoutContext`.



This patch fixes this by changing `CreateLine` to add

propagated break tokens to `NGLineInfo`, and move them to

`NGInlineChildLayoutContext` only if the line layout is final.



Bug: 1429797
